Escherichia Coli Network Analysis

Introduction

Proteins interactions can be described with interaction networks called PPI (Protein-Protein Interaction) and are commonly represented as undirected graphs (whose edges connecting different interacting proteins have no direction). However, PPI are not static systems, indeed they have both space and time dimensions. Microarray expression profiles provide valuable temporal information on protein-protein interactions and network models allow to incorporate the different time dimension. The link between microarray expression profiles and network lays down on the assumption that product of co-regulated genes have higher chances of interacting with each other. The temporal characteristics of hub proteins (protein with high degree, i.e., proteins connected to many other proteins) is determined by computing the correlation of their mRNA expression with the expressions for their partner proteins. This computation allowed to determine two main types of hub:

  • Party hub(intra-module hubs): hub proteins with relatively high correlations between their mRNA levels and the one of partners. Party hub proteins are assumed to be interacting with their partners concurrently. They have local role in a network, with strong connections within functional modules

  • Date hub(inter-module hubs): hubs with low correlation in the expression levels with their partners, interactin with them at different times. Date hubs interconnect functional modules giving rise to the network topology and consequently have a global role.

This project is focused on the connection between the concepts of party/date hub and the one of betweennes centrality. Betweennes is the typical global centrality measure and commonly used when trying to find bridges that interconnect different functional modules, as what date hubs are supposed to do. It is defined as the number of times a node is part of the shortest path between two other nodes. When a node has high importance within the graph, a large number of the shortest paths pass trough the node in the graph itself.

It’s in dataset form and it’s formed by different variables but we will consider only few of them for this project:

  • Protein1/2: two columns representing protein 1 interacting with protein 2;

  • Experiments: indicator for the confidence, goodness of the reported interaction. The higher, the more valuable the interaction;

To retain “good qualities” interaction, we need to look at the distribution of the “experiments” value. Interactions with a confidence equal to 0 can be excluded since represents interactions not experimentally validated.

## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

The confidence of interactions follows a sort of bimodal distribution when its value is below 500 and shows a peak of good confidence interactions around 800. Different analyses will be initialized varying the treshold filtering upon confidence. In particular, 3 tresholds will be set leading to 3 different analyses:

  1. High-Confidence interactions: minExp > 600
  2. Mid-Confidence Interaction minExp > 250
  3. Low-Confidence Interaction minExp > 0

The different results obtained by the analyses will be compared to establish whether the loss of information given by the exclusion of low-confidence interaction does not affect the quality of the results.

Node categories

Nodes are splitted into 4 categories:

  1. Bottleneck hubs (BH): hubs with high degree and betweenness
  2. Non-Bottleneck Hubs (NBH): hubs with high degree but low betwenness
  3. Bottleneck non-Hubs (BNH): node with high betweenness but low degree
  4. Non-Bottleneck non-Hubs (NBNH): node with low betweenness and degree.

In order to properly distinguish high betweenness/degree from low values, a treshold for quantiles can be set. In this case a soft one is used (0.9) for both parameters. This allows to group the nodes with the best values for these parameters into the top 10% given by the quantile.

###define centrality measures for betweenness and degree

eco_ppi_hq_betwennes <-betweenness(eco_ppi_graph_hq,directed=FALSE)

eco_ppi_hq_degree<- degree(eco_ppi_graph_hq)

### defining threshold  
treshold <- 0.9 

betwenness_treshold <-quantile(eco_ppi_hq_betwennes,treshold)

degree_treshold <-quantile(eco_ppi_hq_degree,treshold)

#categorize nodes 

BH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_hq)$name[eco_ppi_hq_betwennes>=betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_hq_degree>=degree_treshold]

#non-bottleneck hubs (NBH)
NBH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_hq)$name[eco_ppi_hq_betwennes<betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_hq_degree>=degree_treshold]

#bottleneck non-hub (BNH)
BNH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_hq)$name[eco_ppi_hq_betwennes>=betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_hq_degree<degree_treshold]

#non bottleneck non hubs NBNH
NBNH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_hq)$name[eco_ppi_hq_betwennes<betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_hq_degree<degree_treshold]

Compute neighborhood for each type

Neighborhood for each node type is computed by considering only the neighbors and not the hub itself. This is because the aim of this project is to proper classify date and party hubs considering correlation in expression values. Party hubs should contain several consitutive genes (hub) in which there are not big fluctuations in gene co-expression with their neighbors among different conditions. This means that the computation of correlation in gene expression for these nodes is useless in this persective. For this reason, this step is carried out calculating correlations between interactors of the hub and not between hubs and their interactors.

#computing neighbors and retrieving neighbor genes for BH 
BH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_hq,1, BH)
NBH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_hq, 1, NBH)
BNH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_hq, 1, BNH)
NBNH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_hq, 1, NBNH)

#remove hubs from BH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(BH_neighbors)) {
  BH_neighbors[[i]] <- BH_neighbors[[i]][BH_neighbors[[i]]$name != BH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from NBH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(NBH_neighbors)) {
  NBH_neighbors[[i]] <- NBH_neighbors[[i]][NBH_neighbors[[i]]$name != NBH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from BNH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(BNH_neighbors)) {
  BNH_neighbors[[i]] <- BNH_neighbors[[i]][BNH_neighbors[[i]]$name != BNH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from NBNH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(NBNH_neighbors)) {
  NBNH_neighbors[[i]] <- NBNH_neighbors[[i]][NBNH_neighbors[[i]]$name != NBNH[i]]
}

Having computed the neighborhood for each type, now it’s time for correlation values. Both pearson and spearman correlation can be used for this purpose, but the latter should suits best since it doesn’t assume a linear correlation between two variables, in this case between two gene expression values.

In order to exhaustively analyze the different correlation coefficients between hubs’ interactors, we create an interval from -1 (anti-correlation) to 1 (high-correlation) in which the aforementioned coefficient will fall within. This computation approximates the probability density function of the correlation coeffiecient for each hub. It all can be visualized with an heatmap showing for each bin For each category an heatmap describing the strength and of interactions will be plotted, toghether with a hierarchical clustering to evaluate patterns.

The distribution of correlation for each type can also be evaluated with a plot showing a value representing the amount of interaction that falls within a particular bin, for each bin.

Correlation in gene expression for BH

For BH, the distribution is shifted to the right and two peaks can be appreciated: one around 0.5 and the other around 0.8. There are also some anti-correlation interactions.

Correlation in gene expression for NBH

By comparing BH with NBH by looking at pattern in correlations, the former appears to show two areas that divide a more spread distribution (in the lower part) from a slighty more compact one in the upper part. The dendrogram depicting hierchical clustering plotted on the left does not provide a strong result for both BH and NBH.

For NBH, the portion showing date hubs-like pattern is smaller with respect to BH. This is expected since the concept of bottleneckness is strictly linked with date hubs.

The distribution of correlation values for each bin in NBH is not so different with respect to BH for higher values of correlation.

Correlation for identification

Spearman correlation coefficient (SCC) is a powerful tool to differentiate party from date hubs: proteins designated as hubs have sufficiently high degree and their labels could be set as party or date hubs depending on which side of a treshold its SCC score fell on. In this perspective, we can consider the mean and the variance of SCC:

-Mean to understand the size of the coefficients 
-The variance to figure out the shape of the distribution.

We calculate these metrics between all the interactors for each hub. To compute this calculation we will retrieve the correlation matrix between all interactors from BH and NBH.

#we first create a dataframe that store the type, degree and betweenness values for each node
nodes_names <- c(BH, NBH, BNH, NBNH)
stats_hq <- data.frame(row.names = nodes_names, 
                    list(type = c(rep('BH', length(BH)),
                                  rep('NBH', length(NBH)),
                                  rep('BNH', length(BNH)),
                                  rep('NBNH', length(NBNH))),
                    betwenness = eco_ppi_hq_betwennes[nodes_names],
                    degree = eco_ppi_hq_degree[nodes_names]))
                    
centralities <- cbind(stats_hq$degree, stats_hq$betwenness)

We now plot the distribution of the mean and variance coefficients for BH and NBH to check for differences between the two. Party hubs should show higher levels of correlations in expression with their neighbors with respect to date hubs.For this reason, the result can be not as expected since, considering the bottleckness definition, NBH should be enriched in party hubs. The figure above shows the probabily density function which, for NBH case, is a differently-weighted average of the bell-shaped p.d.f.s of the two normal distributions. The weights are not equal and thus peaks have different heights. The two peaks are divided by a value of meanSCC ~ 0.6. As in https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pcbi.1000817, they say that the date/party distinction was originally motivated by an approximately bimodal distribution of hub co-expression. Considering this paper, the right bell of the distribution can be attributed to the presence of party hub whereas the left to date ones, with an higher presence of date hubs in NBH. Even though the difference in the shape of the curves are not so evident, this result can be somewhat conflicting with the definition of bottleneckness: given their nature, NBH should more enriched in party hubs w.r.t date hubs. A similar consideration can be made for BH, which should be enriched in date hubs and thus should show lower level of correlation with their neighbors.

We can also take a look at the variance:

ggplot(metrics_hq) + 
  geom_density(aes(x=varSCC, fill=type)) +
  ggtitle("varSCC among interactors") + 
  ylab("Density") + 
  xlab("varSCC") +
  theme_light()

Both BH and NBH shows a p.d.f.s shifted to the left, meaning that the correlation values does not vary much from the mean.

To confirm the presence of bimodality in hubs, we can plot the distribution of the overall mean value for SCC.

ggplot(metrics_hq) +
  geom_density(aes(x=meanSCC)) + 
  xlab("meanSCC") +
  ggtitle("Density plot for meanSCC distribution") + 
  theme_light()

Bimodality is appreciated, and, by looking at the plot, the classification of date/party hub can be carried out using a treshold of ~ 0.55 for meanSCC, such that whatever is under the treshold can be considered date hub and party hub over the treshold

To validate these results we can use dimensionality reduction trying to classificate date/party hubs using the treshold aforementioned for meanSCC.

There is a very similar number of party and date hubs. Now we can use PCA dimensionality reduction to check if hubs clusterize according to their type. To display the PCA plot i need the transposed matrix containing the distribution of normalized counts for each node/protein representing how many interaction falls within each bin of correlation.

normalized_counts <- function(corr_vector) {
  hist <- hist(corr_vector, breaks=intervals, plot = F)
  count <- hist$counts/sum(hist$counts)
  names(count) <- hist$mids
  return(count)
}

hubs_counts_hq <- sapply(spearmans_vector_hq, normalized_counts)
color <- ifelse((classification == 'Date'), "red", "blue")
pca_plot <- prcomp(t(hubs_counts_hq), scale = F, center = F)
autoplot(pca_plot, colour = color, label =TRUE , shape = F)

Hubs clusterize quite well along the first principal components (even though it explains only 40,04% of the total variance) according to the date(red) or party(blue) membership

Another dimensionality reduction technique can be applied to better infer and eventually confirm the presence of patterns in data. Umap visualization is based on the correct number of PCA principal components able to explain all the variance in data. In order to properly select the number of Principal components, we can use the so-called elbow plot.

pcs <- paste0("PC", seq(1,dim(pca_plot$rotation)[2]), sep = "")
pcs <- factor(pcs, level = pcs)
var = summary(pca_plot)$importance[2,]
variances <- as.data.frame(list(pc = pcs,
                                var = var))
ggplot(variances, aes(x = pc, y = var, group = 1)) + 
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() + 
  theme_light()

We can see that the variance is spread across several components. For Umap visualization it is preferable using a number of PCs well beyond the elbow. We choose 15 PCs.

U<-umap(t(hubs_counts_hq), pca=15, n_components = 3)
plot3d(x=U[,1],y=U[,2],z=U[,3], col=color)
rglwidget()

From the umap we can appreciate an even clearer division between date and party hubs.

Given all these considerations, we can now create party and date hubs categories, using and try to biologically validate them.

party_hubs_hq <- as.list(filter(metrics_hq, metrics_hq$meanSCC > meanSCC_treshold))[1]
date_hubs_hq<- as.list(filter(metrics_hq, metrics_hq$meanSCC <= meanSCC_treshold))[1]

NBNH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_mq)$name[eco_ppi_mq_betwennes<betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_mq_degree<degree_treshold]

The distribution of each centrality measure can be computted.

nodes_names <- c(BH, NBH, BNH, NBNH)
stats_mq <- data.frame(row.names = nodes_names, 
                    list(type = c(rep('BH', length(BH)),
                                  rep('NBH', length(NBH)),
                                  rep('BNH', length(BNH)),
                                  rep('NBNH', length(NBNH))),
                    betwenness = eco_ppi_mq_betwennes[nodes_names],
                    degree = eco_ppi_mq_degree[nodes_names]))
                    
centralities_mq <- cbind(stats_mq$degree, stats_mq$betwenness)
#calculate the mean for each group and for each stat
mean_deg <- ddply(stats_mq, 'type', summarise, grp.mean_deg = mean(degree))
mean_bet <- ddply(stats_mq, 'type', summarise, grp.mean_bet = mean(betwenness))

degree_distr <- ggplot(stats_mq, aes(x=degree, fill=type)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4)+
  geom_vline(data=mean_deg, aes(xintercept=grp.mean_deg, color=type),

Compute neighborhood for each type

#computing neighbors and retrieving neighbor genes for BH 
BH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_mq,1, BH)
NBH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_mq, 1, NBH)
BNH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_mq, 1, BNH)
NBNH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_mq, 1, NBNH)

#remove hubs from BH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(BH_neighbors)) {
  BH_neighbors[[i]] <- BH_neighbors[[i]][BH_neighbors[[i]]$name != BH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from NBH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(NBH_neighbors)) {
  NBH_neighbors[[i]] <- NBH_neighbors[[i]][NBH_neighbors[[i]]$name != NBH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from BNH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(BNH_neighbors)) {
  BNH_neighbors[[i]] <- BNH_neighbors[[i]][BNH_neighbors[[i]]$name != BNH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from NBNH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(NBNH_neighbors)) {
  NBNH_neighbors[[i]] <- NBNH_neighbors[[i]][NBNH_neighbors[[i]]$name != NBNH[i]]
}

Correlation in gene expression for BH

Also in this case it appears that date hubs patterns are in the lower part of the heatmap, as it can be seen from the dendrogram on the left. Results are overall more dense and noisy, due to the contribution of lower-confidence PPI. The plot showing the amount of interactions falling within each bin of correlation shows a peak around 0.5, with greater low-correlation interaction w.r.t high quality PPI analysis.

Correlation in gene expression for NBH

By comparing BH with NBH by looking at pattern in correlations, we can now see results more coherent with NBH and BH natures. Indeed, in NBH the peak is slightly more shifted to the right, displaying more high correlation levels interactions, in concordance with party hubs patterns.

Correlation in gene expression for BNH and NBNH

#### Correlation in gene expression for NBNH

#NBNH contains neighborhood with only one interactor. These can be removed 
mask <- array()

  mask[i] <- length(NBNH_neighbors[[i]]) != 1
}
NBNH_neighbors <- NBNH_neighbors[mask]

BNH and NBNH display some patterns for this part of the analysis, especially NBNH in which are depicted two main areas that differentiate between a less and a more spread distribution. However, we cannot cut the dendrogram in order to have two main clusters (corresponding to the areas) since the upper part appears to be noisy and with several anti-correlation interactions.

Correlation for identification

We can directly appreciate the loss of bimodality (not considering the left peak for BH, probably given by noisy interactions). However, the meanSCC for NBH now is slightly higher than BH and this is an expected outcome given NBH and BH definitions.

Variance:

ggplot(metrics_mq) + 
  geom_density(aes(x=varSCC, fill=type)) +
  ggtitle("varSCC among interactors") + 
  ylab("Density") + 
  xlab("varSCC") +

Here the difference with high-confidence PPI is remarkable, but expected. The inclusion of lower confidence interactions lead to a more spread variance around the mean value for both BH and NBH, where the former shows two peak (the first around 0.05 and the second 0.12).

To confirm the presence of bimodality in hubs, we can plot the distribution of the overall mean value for SCC.

ggplot(metrics_mq) +
  geom_density(aes(x=meanSCC)) + 
  xlab("meanSCC") +
  ggtitle("Density plot for meanSCC distribution") + 
  theme_light()

The bimodality necessary for the classification is totally lost. Given the design of this analysis, it’s then hard to select a treshold for properly distinguish party hubs from date hubs and, as a consequence, to continue the rest of the analysis.

Low-Confidence Protein-Protein Interactions Analysis

The same procedures followed in the High/Mid-Confidence part of the analysis will now be applied using all the PPI interaction.

###define centrality measures for betweenness and degree

eco_ppi_lq_betwennes <-betweenness(eco_ppi_graph_lq,directed=FALSE)

eco_ppi_lq_degree<- degree(eco_ppi_graph_lq)

### defining threshold  
treshold <- 0.9 

betwenness_treshold <-quantile(eco_ppi_lq_betwennes,treshold)
betwenness_treshold <- round(betwenness_treshold, digits = 2)

degree_treshold <-quantile(eco_ppi_lq_degree,treshold)

#categorize nodes 

BH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_lq)$name[eco_ppi_lq_betwennes>=betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_lq_degree>=degree_treshold]

#non-bottleneck hubs (NBH)
NBH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_lq)$name[eco_ppi_lq_betwennes<betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_lq_degree>=degree_treshold]

#bottleneck non-hub (BNH)
BNH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_lq)$name[eco_ppi_lq_betwennes>=betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_lq_degree<degree_treshold]

#non bottleneck non hubs NBNH
NBNH<-V(eco_ppi_graph_lq)$name[eco_ppi_lq_betwennes<betwenness_treshold & eco_ppi_lq_degree<degree_treshold]

The distribution of each centrality measure can be visualized.

nodes_names_lq <- c(BH, NBH, BNH, NBNH)
stats_lq <- data.frame(row.names = nodes_names_lq, 
                    list(type = c(rep('BH', length(BH)),
                                  rep('NBH', length(NBH)),
                                  rep('BNH', length(BNH)),
                                  rep('NBNH', length(NBNH))),
                    betwenness = eco_ppi_lq_betwennes[nodes_names_lq],
                    degree = eco_ppi_lq_degree[nodes_names_lq]))
                    
centralities_lq <- cbind(stats_lq$degree, stats_lq$betwenness)
#calculate the mean for each group and for each stat
mean_deg <- ddply(stats_lq, 'type', summarise, grp.mean_deg = mean(degree))
mean_bet <- ddply(stats_lq, 'type', summarise, grp.mean_bet = mean(betwenness))

degree_distr <- ggplot(stats_lq, aes(x=degree, fill=type)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4)+
  geom_vline(data=mean_deg, aes(xintercept=grp.mean_deg, color=type),
             linetype="dashed") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = degree_treshold, size = 1 ) +
  geom_label(aes(x=degree_treshold +22, y = 0.8, label =paste('Degree treshold: ', degree_treshold))) +

Compute neighborhood for each type

#computing neighbors and retrieving neighbor genes for BH 
BH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_lq,1, BH)
NBH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_lq, 1, NBH)
BNH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_lq, 1, BNH)
NBNH_neighbors <- neighborhood(eco_ppi_graph_lq, 1, NBNH)

#remove hubs from BH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(BH_neighbors)) {
  BH_neighbors[[i]] <- BH_neighbors[[i]][BH_neighbors[[i]]$name != BH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from NBH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(NBH_neighbors)) {
  NBH_neighbors[[i]] <- NBH_neighbors[[i]][NBH_neighbors[[i]]$name != NBH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from BNH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(BNH_neighbors)) {
  BNH_neighbors[[i]] <- BNH_neighbors[[i]][BNH_neighbors[[i]]$name != BNH[i]]
}

#remove hubs from NBNH neighbors
for (i in 1:length(NBNH_neighbors)) {
  NBNH_neighbors[[i]] <- NBNH_neighbors[[i]][NBNH_neighbors[[i]]$name != NBNH[i]]
}

Conclusions

In This analysis, we have tried to classify date and party hubs using correlation in expression values among all the interactors for a given hub, not considering the hub itself. After having categorized nodes according to their degree (hubs vs non-hubs) and for their betwenness value (bottleneck hubs vs non-bottleneck hubs), we have carried three different analyses based on a parameter representing how reliable interactions are. Best classificaition and results were given by considering only high-confidence interactions, meaning that not only information loss (given by exclusion of low-confidence PPI) does not compromise the goodness of the results, but it does improve them.

Classification of Party/Date hubs using Semantic Similarity measures

A further attempt that can biologically validate and proper classify hubs into date and party hub was given by Kenley et al. that introduced a novel measure for such aim based on semantic similarity measures integrated with GO data. Combined with the centrality measures of degree, betweennes and closeness, this measure can detect potential party and date hubs. Gene Ontology maintains a controlled vocabulary of gene and gene products attributes in a directed acyclic graph. (DAG). Gene and proteins are annotated to the most specific GO terms within three orthogonal ontologies: biological processes, molecular functions and cellular components. Functional similarities between two proteins can be assessed by measuring semantic similarity between GO terms having the annotation of the proteins. There are different semantic similarity measures that can be applied, but the one which appears to yield the best results is the information-content-based semantic similarity one. It calculates the information content of the most specific common ancestors of two terms, i.e., the negative log-likelihood of a term c. The likelihood of a term can be estimated by the proportion of annotating proteins to the term in GO. This method can be normalized by individual information contents of two terms of interest or by their likelihood. This paper demonstrates that the information content-based-method (Resnik’s method) with the best-matching evaluation criterion (it chooses the highest semantic similarity of all possible combinations between two terms) has the highest accuracy on measuring functional similarities of protein pairs than other semantic similarity measures. Using this approach, the detected hubs (Bottleneck and non-bottleneck) can be split into party and date based on the average semantic similarity. If the average semantic similarity score between the hub and its neighbors is greater than a treshold lambda (scrivi lambda), it can be classified into a party hub, date otherwise. The purpose of this analysis stands in the comparison between results yielded by the Resnik’s method with the ones previously obtained. In this perspective, package `GOSemSim` will be used.

Information content-based method

The method proposed by Resnik are information content (IC) based, which depends on the frequencies of two GO terms involved and that of their closest common ancestors term in a specific corpus of GO annotations. The information content of a GO term is computed by the negative log probability of the term occurring in GO corpus. A rarely used term contains a greater amount of information. The frequency of a term t is defined as:

\[ p(t) = \frac{n_{t}}N|t^i \in \{t,childrenoft\} \] where nt’ is the number of term t’, and N is the total number of GO corpus.

Thus the information content is defined as.

\[ IC(t) = -log(p(t)) \] As GO allow multiple parents for each concept, two terms can share parents by multiple paths. IC-based methods calculate similarity of two GO terms based on the information content of their closest common ancestor term, which is also called Most Informative Common Ancestor (MICA).

Resnik’s method

The Resnik’s method is defined as:

\[ sim_{Resnik}(t_1,t_2) = IC(MICA) \]

Since a gene product can be annotated my multiple GO terms, semantic similarity among gene products need to be aggregated from different semantic similarity scores of multiple GO terms associated with genes, including max, avg, rcmax and BMA. For this project, we will use average semantic similarity score:

\[ sim_{avg}(g1,g2) = \frac{\sum_{i = 1}^{m} \sum_{j = 1}^{n} sim(go_{1i},go_{2j})}{\ m * n} \]

Summary

The idea behind semantic similarity measurement is the notion than genes (or gene products) with similar function should have similar annotation vocabulary and have a close relationship in the ontology structure. Similar object tend to behave similarly, which supports many applications to infer gene (gene products) functions but also, as in our case, protein-protein interactions

In order to be coherent with the best results yielded in previous analyses, we will use Resnik’s method only on hubs composed by high-quality PPI.

As in [1] a hub protein is labeled as party hub if it shares at least one functional module with its neighbors with a higher percentage above the treshold (they used a treshold of 0.5). Date party in the other way aroud. In this perspective i create a function to retrieve the name for each interactor for each hub.

id_to_name <- function (neighbor) {
  names <- A[match(neighbor$name, A$`Protein ID`),1]
  neighbor <- vector()
  neighbor <- names
  return(neighbor)
}

hubs_neighbors_name <- lapply(hubs_neighbors_hq, id_to_name)

Now i create a function that takes as input the neighborhood for hubs and compute the average semantic similarity measures for each group of interaction have to apply mgeneSim function, which calculates semantic similarity measure for a group of interactors for a given hub. We thus labeled a hub protein a party hub if it shares at least one functional module with its neighbors with a higher percentage of the threshold (for our experiments we used a threshold of 0.5). In other words, it is a party hub if the neighbors of a higher percentage of the threshold belong to the same functional modules to the hub protein. On the other hand, a hub protein is labeled as a date hub if the percentage for each functional module it shares with its neighbors does not exceed the threshold (the same threshold for both party and date hubs).

find_party_hubs <- function (neighborhood, treshold) {
  matrix <- mgeneSim(neighborhood, semData=Eck12_GO, measure="Resnik", combine="avg", verbose=FALSE)
  party_hubs_semsim <- names(mean(rowSums(matrix)[1]) > treshold)
  return(party_hubs_semsim)
}

find_date_hubs <- function (neighborhood, treshold) {
  matrix <- mgeneSim(neighborhood, semData=Eck12_GO, measure="Resnik", combine="avg", verbose=FALSE)
  date_hubs_semsim = vector()
  date_hubs_semsim <- c(date_hubs_semsim, names(mean(rowSums(matrix)[1]) <= treshold))
  return(date_hubs_semsim)
}
